          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">
          South Korea‚Äôs quiet competition
</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/south-korean-k9-thunder-howitzers-live-fire-drill.png" alt="South Korean K9 Thunder howitzers fire during a live-fire drill" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>South Korean K9 Thunder howitzers fire during a live-fire drill. Credits: Dong-a Ilbo/AFP via Getty Images</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         South Korea quietly established itself as a key player in the global arms market. Between 2021 and 2023, its defense exports increased by 140%, from $7.2B to $17.3B. The international interest in their K2 Black Panther tanks, K9 self-propelled howitzers, and FA-50 light fighters has positioned South Korea among the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-22-04-2025-h1-1-top-10-arms-exporters" target="_blank">top 10 arms exporters</a>, alongside France, Russia, and the US.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Korea‚Äôs quicker delivery, favorable pricing, and willingness to localize production (allowing countries to use parts made in their own countries) set a precedent for where Europe buys its arms.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         South Korea‚Äôs surge is powered by its private tech sector. Firms like Hanwha Aerospace, LIG Nex1, and Hyundai Rotem help develop capabilities such as AI-powered targeting systems, autonomous vehicle guidance, and encrypted battlefield comms. Their R&D budgets also increased to $5.1B, providing them an edge over European contractors.</p>
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         While the United States remains the leader in absolute arms export volume, South Korea‚Äôs exports surged by 15%, outpacing traditional players.</p>
        </mj-text>
