          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">How is the next pope chosen, and who are the likely candidates?
</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/21-new-cardinals-diplomats-advisors-administrators.png" alt="The group of 21 new cardinals includes diplomats, advisors, and administrators" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>The group of 21 cardinals includes diplomats, advisors, and administrators. Credits: Filippo Monteforte, AFP</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">    
           The process of <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-22-04-2025-f1-8-choosing-a-pope" target="_blank">choosing a Pope</a> begins with the Cardinal Chamberlain and the Vatican health department confirming the death of the current Pope. Then, the College of Cardinals meets in a private conclave to elect a successor. Cardinals under the age of 80 can vote. Currently, there are 135 eligible electors.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          The conclave takes place in the Sistine Chapel, where cardinals are isolated from the outside world to ensure secrecy. Voting occurs several times a day until a two-thirds majority is reached. If no decision is made after 33 ballots, a run-off is held between the top candidates. Once elected, the Pope chooses a papal name and is presented from the balcony of St. Peter‚Äôs Basilica.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Who will be elected remains speculative. The Church may prioritize inclusivity or choose someone from a region where Catholicism is still growing. Notably, Pope Francis appointed 108 of the 135 voting cardinals, increasing the chances of a Pope who shares his progressive, inclusive vision.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Among the top 12 contenders (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-22-04-2025-f1-9-interactive-website" target="_blank">interactive website</a>) is Cardinal Robert Sarah of Guinea, representing Africa, home to nearly 20% of the world‚Äôs Catholics. Another strong candidate is Cardinal Luis Antonio Gokim Tagle of the Philippines, often described as the ‚ÄúAsian version of Pope Francis.‚Äù</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Interestingly, half of the top 12 contenders are from Europe. Some represent nations without Catholic majorities, such as Sweden and the Netherlands, while others hail from Congo, Myanmar, and the United States.</p>
